@{fg shine}The Locket [#38]@{fg text}

Today the Banik, Stark, the man Crichton was imprisoned with on the Peacekeeper Gammak base, returned unexpectedly to Moya to return the transport she had loaned him. It was pleasing to see another friendly face, even if, in Stark's case, it was only half a face, the other half concealed by the mask he wears. There are far too few friendly faces in the galaxy, it seems. Stark's was certainly quite welcomed.

We were deep in the Uncharted Territories, continuing our search for safe avenues in which to hide from Scorpius and our other unfriendly pursuers. Moya came across a kind of nebulous net in space, and at first it seemed like a serendipitous discovery; inside the nebula we could be reasonably certain we wouldn't be tracked.

Officer Sun decided to scout out the net before Moya entered, and she departed the ship in her prowler to analyse and report. Patiently, we waited.

Eight arns later, when Aeryn had not returned nor contacted us, the crew and I grew concerned. We entered the net in the hopes of locating Officer Sun's prowler.

I was somewhat dubious, and at first I feared the worst. But shortly after entering the net, Moya identified a kind of schism and from out it, thankfully, Aeryn's prowler emerged.

We should know by now that fortune does not treat us so kindly. When Aeryn reboarded Moya, she was changed, greatly changed. Eight arns prior she had left us as a healthy, vital young woman. Now she was withered, wrinkled and greyed. She informed us that she had indeed aged; she had lived fifty-five years during the eight arns that passed aboard Moya. How this was possible, I do not know. But I trust Officer Sun implicitly, and when she claimed to have lived on a planet for fifty-five years, married, and was now a grandmother, I believed her without hesitation.

Her granddaughter was waiting for her, she said. She needed to go back.

Through the schism there was, she explained, an alternate dimension, in which there was a planet with a community she had joined. The schism would be closing soon, and if she were to make it safely through she needed to leave promptly. She said... she just wanted to see us one last time. I am truly glad she did.

Commander Crichton insisted on joining her through the schism, and when he returned, alone, he confirmed her account. The schism did indeed open on an alternate dimension, and every eight arns that passed here meant fifty-five years on the other side. The schism closed behind Crichton, not to open again for another eight arns.

Crichton swore he would return in eight arns to retrieve Officer Sun and return with her to Moya. She would have aged another fifty-five years in that time, but Sebaceans have long life-expectancies and she would likely still be alive. Hesitantly, the crew agreed to allow Crichton through.

It is now two arns since Crichton left us. He did not return, as promised, before the schism closed, and we can only assume he is in the alternate dimension with Officer Sun. We will wait here for another six arns, in the hopes that they will return to us.

If they do, then perhaps we can find a way to reverse the effects of the aging process, though it is my opinion that the prospect is grim. However, Moya is their home, and even aged, this is where they belong.

So we will wait here for Crichton to return with Aeryn. And we will hope, and we will pray, that they both come back to us intact... and alive.

@EndNode

