@{fg shine}The Ugly Truth [#39]@{fg text}

Talyn returned to us as suddenly as he had left. Moya's relief was so strong that I found myself unable to sense anything other than her maternal instincts: her concern that Crais had treated Talyn well, her sheer joy at seeing her offspring once again, and her fear over the violent impulses she detected within him.

Crais requested that several of us meet him aboard Talyn. He specified that our crew should bring no weapons, and he promised that the meeting would be conducted peaceably. Unbelievably, he appeared to be seeking our help.

Shortly after Officer Sun boarded Talyn, followed by Crichton, D'Argo, Zhaan, and the former slave Stark, a Plokavians weapons trade ship approached their coordinates and opened communication with Crais. Just a few microts later, the Plokavian ship was destroyed - shot by an energy beam coming from Talyn's forward cannon.

The crew retreated to the transport leaving Crais and Talyn to starburst away. Meanwhile, a second Plokavian ship, determined to discover who was to blame for the destruction of their associates' vessel, incapacitated the group on the transport with a kind of shockwave and brought them aboard for interrogation.

Chiana and Rygel felt we should stay and make an attempt to rescue the crew from the Plokavians - a race known to be at once extremely violent and passionately committed to bringing about justice - but Moya had alternate designs. As this brief reunion with Talyn ended so disastrously, Moya was more committed than ever to find him at all costs. So at her request I programmed a search pattern, on the infinitesimal chance we would be able to catch up with Talyn wherever his starburst had taken him.

Back on the Plokavian vessel, the crew was captive atop a solitary platform high above a large open, empty space. One by one, each member was brought into the audience of the Plokavians and asked to recount his or her view of the events leading to the destruction of the weapons trade ship. If any of them attempted to lie, all would be executed - but if the guilty party would confess, only that person would be forced to face death by dispersal.

After the last testimony was heard, the Plokavians inquisitors came forward with their verdict. Each crew members account of the events had been different, leading them to believe they were being lied to by the crew.

With no one person willing to take the blame, the Plokavians decreed that only one thing could be done. The entire crew would have to be put to death.

@EndNode

@Node FSCP40 "Farscape"
@{LINDENT 1}
@{fg shine}A Clockwork Nebari [#40]@{fg text}

I am not sure if we will ever know if Stark was able to survive the Plokavian dispersal, but even beyond that sacrifice he left a great legacy aboard Moya. It was Stark who informed D'Argo that his son Jothee was alive, and it was this information that led John, Aeryn, Chiana and Rygel out in pursuit of further information regarding Jothee. However, to that end, Chiana entered into her own particular breed of... negotiation with some men who proved to be just a bit more than she could handle.

After they returned to Moya, Chiana was certain Aeryn would express her displeasure at Chiana's uncanny ability to find - or cause - trouble. But when she came to confront Chiana, rather than being enraged Aeryn appeared calm, even apologetic for not being able to better protect the Nebari girl. This entirely uncharacteristic behavior from Officer Sun alerted both Chiana and John to the fact that Aeryn was affected by some sort of artificial influence, and when they saw the companion she had brought aboard Moya, their suspicions were confirmed.

A Nebari female named Varla had come aboard the ship, and had mind-cleansed Aeryn and Rygel, leaving them in the same state of blissful idiocy we'd seen from Durka over a cycle ago when Chiana was first brought aboard. Varla incarcerated John and D'Argo while making preparations to clense them as well. Apparently their mind-cleansing drugs could not affect my particular physiology, so instead they cruelly locked me in a heavy collar with which they could control me and... kill me should I decide not to obey their wishes.

Varla and her associate, Meelak, we learned, had come to try and gain information from Chiana regarding Chiana's brother Nerri, whom Chiana had believed to be dead when the life disk she carried in her stomach ceased to transmit.

For the Nebari, despite their insistant espousal of a "greater good," for all, were carrying out serious and terrifying plot. Nerri, they said, was part of a resistance aimed to stop it.

Chiana explained that many cycles ago, she, Nerri, and others like them were infected with a contagion during what they were told were "routine physical examinations". This contagion - transmitted through intimate contact - was to be spread throughout many alien systems in the area. When the Nebari were ready it would be activated, rendering all who were infected weak and defenseless against subsequent Nebari invasion.

Soon the entire crew with the exception of Chiana and myself were mind-cleansed, leaving no one to stop Varla from her planned rendezvous with the Nebari fleet.

Just when I was certain there would be no escape, Commander Crichton came to me and informed me that he had been able to break through the drug-induced mind-cleansing, and needed my help to rescue Chiana from the Nebari plot.

It would not be easy, though, with Aeryn, D'Argo and Zhaan - lulled into complacency by the mind-cleansing - prowling Moya's corridors at the bidding of our unwelcomed guests, determined to stop any activity not supported by the Nebari. The DRDs had all been deactivated and if I tried to starburst away from the planned rendezvous coordinates, the horrid collar I wore would surely kill me. Despite John's best intentions, I feared Varla had us out-manuvered.

Able to effortlessly destroy Peacekeeper Command Carriers, kill free will and now weaken the galaxy with a self-made plague, the Nebari were proving to be a more dangerous force than any of us had reckoned. In the face of that, what hope was there for a collared Pilot and a seemingly unbalanced human?

