@{fg shine}...Different Destinations [#49]@{fg text}

Even if we did not speak of it, we mourned the loss of Pa'u Zotoh Zhaan, and our longing to ease our pain brought us to the ruins of an old monastery. There, a memorial shrine stood, which commemorated the bravery of Peacekeepers - for once seeming to act in accordance with their name - who died defending Jacacean nurses from the brutal, invading Venek Horde, who had laid seige to the nurses' compound.

History records - well, used to record - that Peacekeeper Sub-Officer Dacon was particularly brave, as it was Dacon's heroic death that enabled the Venek commander, General Grynes, to offer a truce. The idea that merciless, cruel Peacekeepers were instrumental in achieving actual peace struck all of us save former PK Aeryn Sun as something of an irony.

Crichton, Aeryn, D'Argo, Jool and Stark had gone down to visit the memorial, while I monitored repairs to Moya's condensers. On board, Chiana, Rygel, and I realized something was wrong when I received a communication from the planet in the Venek language. This was perplexing, as the Veneks had abandoned the planet hundreds of cycles ago. Then, I received a frantic call from Jool, who was exclaiming that the memorial had changed and was now hung with Venek banners. When we brought her aboard, she showed us a terrible wound on her arm, and she explained what had happened.

Built around a tear in time's fabric, the memorial could show visitors the monastery's famous history, if one wore a special visor. Hoping this triumph of peace would bring comfort to Stark, who especially mourned Zhaan, Crichton had urged him to look at the past. Somehow, Stark's interaction with the tear threw Crichton, Aeryn, D'Argo and Jool back in time, at the precise moment of the Venek attack. Within microts, Jool was shot by a flaming Venek arrow. Quickly, Stark sought the time-tear and D'Argo pushed Jool into it, with the rest planning to follow. But history had somehow been changed, and the tear closed up after Jool passed through it.

I checked computer records, which confirmed that the presence of Crichton and the others in the past was distorting our present. The planet's population was now drastically reduced, and its history files now spoke of a massive war, instead of a truce.

Meanwhile, the group worked to restore the timeline. When Crichton discovered that the Venek commander, General Grynes, was a prisoner in the compound, he tried to sneak him over the wall so that the general would be free to broker the truce. But just as Grynes was escaping, one of the Jocaceans, Nurse Kelsa, shot and killed him. Outside, the Veneks screamed for blood to avenge their general and announced that they would attack at dawn and slaughter all within the monastery.

Crichton insisted to Aeryn and D'Argo that the timeline could still be restored if Sub-Officer Dacon still sacrificed himself. But with the timeline so muddied, Aeryn and D'Argo were not convinced. Regardless, our friends were still trapped in the past, in a compound under seige, and expecting to perish in the morning.

Of course on Moya, we had no way of knowing what new history was being made 500 cycles back. We could only watch as the planet changed before our very eyes from a green, living place to one utterly dead, burning with radiation from a conflict so massive that no life whatsoever had survived. And a short while later, the planet itself disappeared entirely.

It would seem our accidental time-travelers had reshaped history in a manner that resulted in the loss of billions of lives - very possibly including their own.

@EndNode

@Node FSCP50 "Farscape"
@{LINDENT 1}
@{fg shine}Eat Me [#50]@{fg text}

I'm still not sure why Jool's mishandling of the controls caused such catastrophic damage to the transport pod in which she, Crichton, D'Argo, and Chiana were flying. What matters is that they managed to steer the crippled pod toward a Leviathan - and were shocked to realize that it was not Moya. It was a completely different ship, restrained by a Peacekeeper control collar. With the pod dying, Crichton insisted that they enter this strange Leviathan. Steeled to face Peacekeepers there, the four were instead attacked by a pack of ravenous creatures.

After fighting these beasts off, Crichton and D'Argo went to scavenge the narium coils and threekay wire they needed for repairs, leaving Chiana and Jool at the pod. In the abandoned corridors, they found more of the strange creatures, as well as the dreadful sights and smells of a dying, decaying Leviathan, but no explanation for what had happened to the ship. At the pod, Chiana set out to find another replacement part, leaving Jool to begin a dark, lonely vigil armed only with a pulse rifle she did not know how to use.

The perversion Crichton next discovered sickens me beyond telling. It was the Leviathan's Pilot, utterly traumatized, missing several arms. The creatures were eating the regenerable limbs as fast as they grew. Worse, the Pilot was not the victim of mere unthinking animals: A sentient being was behind this cruelty. His name was Kaarvok, and, before Crichton and Chiana's horrified eyes, he killed D'Argo and sucked out the Luxan's brain.

Aeryn, Rygel, Stark, and I knew nothing of this. To our surprise, Moya had unexpectedly entered starburst. However, she seldom takes initiative without cause, and upon emerging from starburst we found Talyn drifting before us. Aeryn explored the severely injured ship and found Captain Crais aboard, unconscious. Apparently another ship had battered Talyn - a sobering thought, given Talyn's own considerable firepower. Though Rygel wanted to flee before the attacker returned, the rest of us supported Moya's wish to stay and care for her wounded offspring.

On the dying Leviathan, Crichton and Chiana solemnly burned D'Argo's body. Then, calmed by Crichton, the wounded ship's Pilot explained that this Leviathan, Rovhu, was a prison ship assigned to the transfer of Kaarvok, who was criminally insane. When the ship was attacked by Scarrans and left to drift, Kaarvok escaped and made Rovhu his. Since then, he had allowed his mysterious creatures - the Xarai - to feed on Rovhu and Rohvu's Pilot. He himself had more... exotic tastes.

Kaarvok's next assault took Crichton and Chiana by surprise. Leaving Crichton unconscious, Kaarvok hunted down the fleeing Chiana. When Crichton woke up, he found the Xarai feasting upon Chiana's corpse. In despair, he could only assume that Jool was dead as well - and that he was next.

I am almost glad that Moya and I did not know of these events. Though I doubt Moya would have abandoned her own offspring to help a stranger, facing such a decision would have been wrenching for us both. Even now, we ache to think of their pain, and it chills me to realize that we encountered two brutalized Leviathans in one solar day. I do not like to think that cruelty of such magnitude may be so commonplace.

@EndNode

