@{fg shine}Meltdown [#56]@{fg text}

Face it. It's hard to connect with kids today. Like, we know that Talyn has had some growing pains - who can blame him? On the run, packing heat, and stuck with creepy Crais as a Big Brother. So he has some sort of freak-out and takes off, racing towards the nearest sun, preparing to swan dive into it. He veered off at the last minute but still seemed to be ready to come apart at the seems. Turned out Talyn was "hearing" irresistible radiation pulses from within the sun, some sort of siren call.

Later, when Aeryn and I started repairing some of the damage incurred by Talyn's road trip, my finger got sparked and she kissed it to make it better. We were getting as hot as the inferno outside, and normally I would have no complaints, ask no questions and take no prisoners - Lord knows I'm irrisistible and all - but there was something wrong. Something like, we generally know better than to take a double shot of lovin' while still in danger of being fried.

That's when I noticed the mist seeping into the corridor.

In the Strategy Room, Crais explained that the mist was "Drexim," Talyn's equivalent of adrenaline. It was leaking out because Talyn was so hyped. Best I can figure, the stuff maxed out our biggest emotions. So Rygel was hungry like the wolf. And Crais was stalking around like Patton with dynamite up his butt.

And Stark?

Stark was hearing things, and he followed a mysterious voice to some ghost-woman haunting Talyn's vestigial Pilot's den. This woman, Sierjna, was trapped within the sun. Hearing her story kicked Stark's Stykera side into overdrive. He became obsessed with helping her.

On the bridge, Aeryn, Crais and I searched for a way to stop Talyn from "hearing" the siren pulse. Re-calibrating the shields seemed promising, but to do that, we needed to fix the damaged shield overrides.

Before we could get started, Mu-Quillus, a matter/energy alien with a face like burnt toast, showed up. Of course, this dude pretended to be our pal. He claimed that his home, the sun, was a naturally occurring "Siren Star" that had already killed 83 Leviathans.

Did we trust him? Hell no - he had maniacal bad guy written all over him. So super-soldier Crais tried to blast him into fiery oblivion, a pretty pointless gesture if you ask me. After all, fiery oblivion is probably this critter's favorite nightclub.

Down in the den, Sierjna told Stark that Mu-Quillus had created the pulsing lure. Another ship building race, the Prahtikrah, had hired him to fry the competition. Along the way, he'd snagged Sierjna from a dying leviathan, holding her captive inside the star.

Sierjna hoped that Stark could restore her to life. But she was dren out of luck, 'cause Stark found she was too far along to the Great Beyond to come back. Apparently there's no going back from that, just forward. Then Mu-Quillus arrived, demanding that Sierjna return. She refused. I guess a crazy Banik still beats a molten mass murderer.

Aeryn and I had a shagadelic time fixing conduits. We even finished, despite the fog of Drexim surrounding us. Yeah, baby.

But Talyn turned back toward the sun. The pulses were now shifting unnaturally, too fast for us to compensate. That proved what Stark already knew: Heat Miser was pulling the strings.

I'd almost pinpointed the lure's source when suddenly Talyn's systems went dark. Even Crais' transponder died. Then Stark jumped into the Pilot's seat and formed a neural link to Talyn, overriding all our controls. First we thought he was gonna save the day. But nooooooo. He flew closer to the sun to rescue Sierjna.

Hoping to stop Stark, I shot out Talyn's guidance circuits. For his part, Crais stomped off to kill the "mutineer" who'd taken over "his" ship.

Stark ignored us. Sierjna was ready to let him guide her into death - but the Banik Avenger's mysterious mojo failed at the critical moment. Then Mu-Quillus popped in and stole Sierjna back. Talyn accelerated to ramming speed. Defeated at last, Stark helpfully announced that we were all going to die...

Funny - Aeryn and I were almost too distracted to care.

@EndNode

@Node FSCP57 "Farscape"
@{LINDENT 1}
@{fg shine}Scratch 'N' Sniff [#57]@{fg text}

Moya and I had grown weary of their incessant arguing, so I banished Crichton and the Luxan from Moya, dispatching them to the pleasure planet LoMo for 10 solar days. It was to be an enjoyable exile - so enjoyable that Chiana and Jool went along voluntarily.

I hoped that Crichton and D'Argo would behave with greater calm upon their return. Instead, they came back eight days too early, with a story that strained disbelief. I was angry enough that they returned so early, but the untruthfulness of Crichton made me doubly so. Chiana and Jool were sleeping off whatever pleasure they had encountered on the planet, so I could get no accounting from them, and I was so angry that I couldn't bear to speak to both D'Argo and Crichton.

On LoMo, so Crichton's story went, they'd been seduced by women who spiked their drinks and stole all their currency. That much, I could believe.

But Crichton didn't bother to make the rest of the story even remotely plausible. He claims that, as they struggled to recover, an alien named Raxil warned them that Chiana and Jool were in trouble, and took Crichton and D'Argo to visit a Hangi. This detail in particular revealed Crichton's falseness, since no reasonable being actually believes Hangis exist. They are mythical creatures who supposedly can detach their eyes and leave them in various locations. The eyes send images back to the Hangis, who display the scenes for customers.

According to Crichton, this supposed Hangi displayed images of Chiana accepting a mysterious drug from a strangely seductive man whom Raxil identified as Fe'Tor. Despite Fe'Tor's reputation as a powerful and dangerous man, D'Argo took it upon himself to infiltrate Fe'Tor's mansion. There, he discovered Chiana and Jool, seeming to be in no danger at all and, on the contrary, having a wonderful time. That Chiana and Jool could find immense pleasure on such a world was one of the few aspects of this story that I could believe.

Chiana and Jool refused to leave Fe'Tor's apartments, so Fe'Tor's guards escorted the Luxan out at gunpoint. Humiliated, D'Argo returned and assaulted Raxil. Raxil then spun around and sprayed him with the same substance that Fe'Tor had given Chiana, to demonstrate its qualities. According to Crichton, this drug had unusual, powerful properties. To speak delicately, although Crichton did not, the drug instantly made D'Argo crave intimate companionship.

Raxil explained that this drug, freslin, came in many varieties and was a sexual attractant. The sadistic Fe'Tor made especially high-quality freslin by milking its base element from the senil gland of sentient beings - a process he reportedly took to a deadly extreme. Raxil claimed that Fe'Tor was milking her mate, Sarl. In exchange for her assistance in rescuing Chiana and Jool, Raxil wanted Crichton and D'Argo to help save Sarl.

Then Crichton said that he and D'Argo used the Hangi to spy on Fe'Tor's compound. Next, they retrieved weapons and currency from the transport pod to plan a two-main raid on an auction of "pleasure slaves" Fe'Tor was holding. Chiana was to be featured in the sale.

The following portion of Crichton's tale especially strains plausibility. D'Argo, who had already been identified and thrown out by Fe'Tor once, was sprayed with a special kind of freslin that Raxil called an "aura morph." It created a sensory illusion, which would completely disguise D'Argo in another form, at least until he metabolized the freslin, which would happen more quickly if he didn't stay calm.

Crichton, D'Argo, and Raxil attended the auction, where a weakened Chiana was sold like an animal to the highest bidder. D'Argo's anger at the situation sped up his metabolism, which caused his disguise to evaporate. He and Crichton then began shooting, and in the confusion, rescued both Chiana and Jool.

Crichton's tale ran further, but recounting it just increases my anger, for no matter what lies he tells, Moya and I are having none of it...

@EndNode

