Back on the Command Carrier, Crichton goaded Scorpius into joining him for the dangerous wormhole test flight. It was an ideal distraction. Not only was Scorpius absent from his ship and dazzled by his experience, but his crew was also preoccupied by the event.

With the diversion successful, Aeryn and Crais overcame the guards surrounding Talyn. Aeryn and Crais said farewell, then Crais boarded Talyn for the last time. Once on board, Crais woke the young ship, which was not so incapacitated as Crais had led the Peacekeepers to believe. We'll never know what their final moments were like; we know only that Talyn must have consented to give his life for Crichton's cause.

Thus, as Crichton returned Scorpius to the Command Carrier, Crais' proud voice echoed over its comm system. Scorpius guessed what was happening, but it was too late. Talyn initiated Starburst -

- Moya and I saw the blast of light and knew immediately what it meant. Buffeted by sorrow, we clung to our pride in the bravery of Moya's son.

And though Talyn's task was done, the devastation was only beginning. Aeryn struggled to rescue D'Argo, Chiana, Rygel and Jool, who were still imprisoned deep within the Command Carrier. Elsewhere, Crichton confronted Scorpius' lead researcher, Co-Kura. When Co-Kura refused to abandon his precious wormhole data, Crichton impressed upon him how dangerous that data could be. Convinced, the shaken Co-Kura reminded Crichton that both of them still knew the wormhole equations. Crichton, of course, has never found a way to shed that burden. But Scorpius' cruel Aurora Chair could wipe the knowledge from Co-Kura's mind. Co-Kura bravely insisted that Crichton activate the chair.

